					<head>Talmud Yerushalmi</head>
					<msContents class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85070287" rend="visible">
						<summary>Volume 1 of a portion of the Palestinian Talmud, with a commentary by Solomon ben Joseph Sirillo.</summary>
						<textLang mainLang="tmr" otherLangs="he">Aramaic, Hebrew</textLang>
						<msItem n="0" rend="visible" class="lccn.loc.gov/sh85070287">
							<locus from="1r" to="371v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he">תלמוד ירושלמי</title>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Talmud Yerushalmi</title>
							<listBibl>
								<bibl>
									<ref target="Lehmann_1875"/>
								</bibl>
							</listBibl>
							<note>
								<p>Uniform with Or 2823, <ref target="Margoliouth_1965" type="number">404</ref> (volume 2 of the manuscript).</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="2r" to="25r"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Introduction</title>
							<note>
								<p>The beginning of the preface is wanting, and the extant portion is mutilated. </p>
								<p>Folio 3r contains the order of the tractates. This parts contains constant references to the Talmud Bavli, Tosefta, Sifra and Sifre.</p>
								<p>Folio 21v begins part 1 of the introduction, explaining foreign words used in the text. This chapter is defective at the end.</p>
								<p>Folio 23r gives the order of Amoraim mentioned in the Palestinian Talmud whose names do not occur in the Babylonian Talmud. This part is defective at the beginning.</p>
								<p>Folio 24r begins section 4 of the introduction, which explains the rationale for the sequence of the tractates.</p>
								<p>On folio 25r there is Sirillo's poem.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="25v" to="102r"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Berakhot</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="102r" to="165r"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Pe᾿ah</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="165r" to="226r"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Demaʾi </title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="226r" to="309r"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Kilʾayim</title>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="309r" to="369v"/>
							<title xml:lang="he-Latn-x-lc">Sheḳalim</title>
							<note>
								<p>This tractate interrupts the order of the masekhtot in Seder Zeraʿim.</p>
								<p>The end of Sheḳalim is missing and replaced on the upper part of folio 369r by a piece beginning: <q>קרבנות הצבור</q>.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
						<msItem rend="">
							<locus from="370r" to="371r"/>
							<title xml:lang="en">Notes</title>
							<note>
								<p>Various Talmudical notes in Sirillo's writing.</p>
							</note>
						</msItem>
					</msContents>
					<physDesc rend="visible">
						<p>Paper codex; Sefardi square and semi-cursive script of the 16th century, partially an autograph of the commentator.</p>
						<objectDesc form="codex">
							<supportDesc material="chart">
								<support>Paper codex.</support>
								<extent>371 folios (+ 2 modern paper flyleaves at the beginning and at the end).<dimensions unit="mm" type="leaf">
										<height>285</height>
										<width>185</width>
									</dimensions>
									<dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
										<height>215</height>
										<width>140</width>
									</dimensions>
								</extent>
								<foliation>
									<p>371 folios.</p>
								</foliation>
								<collation>
									<p>Original quiring not established. All levaes stuck on paper (modern restoration).</p>
								</collation>
								<condition>
									<p>Defective at the beginning. Leaves missing after folio 22.</p>
									<p>A number of pages stained or damaged.</p>
								</condition>
							</supportDesc>
							<layoutDesc>
								<layout columns="1 2" ruledLines="40" writtenLines="40">
									<p>The number of the semi-cursive writing is usually 40, but that of the square writing (on the inner part of the page) varies considerably.</p>
									<p>Many marginal notes and comments supplied in various cursive hands, partially in the author's handwriting.</p>
									<p>Running titles.</p>
									<p>Occasional diagrams (e.g. folio 268r).</p>
									<p>Folio 1 is a title page in Hebrew and German (later addition).</p>
								</layout>
							</layoutDesc>
						</objectDesc>
						<handDesc hands="5">
							<summary>Sefardi square and semi-cursive script of the 16th century, partially an autograph of the commentator.</summary>
							<handNote script="Hebrew" scope="sole"/>
						</handDesc>
						<additions>
							<p>3 folded leaves at the end of the volume, of a recent date, in an Ashkenazi cursive script, with notes on Talmudical portions beginning on folio 143v of the same manuscript.</p>
						</additions>
						<bindingDesc>
							<binding>
								<p>Post-1600. Black leather.</p>
								<p>Spine title: Talmud Jerushalmi. Hebrew. Vol. I. Brit. Mus. Oriental 2822.'</p>
							</binding>
						</bindingDesc>
